T1  - Terms of trade shocks and structural adjustment in a small open economy: Dutch disease and oil price increases
AU  - Fardmanesh, Mohsen
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 34
IS  - 1
SP  - 339
EP  - 353
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/11/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(90)90089-T
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438789090089T
AB  - A three-sector three-factor general equilibrium model of ‘Dutch Disease’ is developed providing yet another explanation for the expansion of the manufacturing sector in most of the oil-exporting countries and the concurrent decline in their agricultural sectors in the 1970s. The sectoral structure of the oil-exporting ‘small’ open economy is altered by an increase in its national income (the spending effect) and in the world price of manufactured goods relative to agricultural products (the world-price effect). While both effects undermine the agricultural sector, the world-price effect may offset the negative impact of the spending effect on the manufacturing sector, resulting in its expansion. The short-run analysis is of the standard Jones specific-factors model. In the long run, the capital rental and the price of the non-traded good are determined by world prices, and the transfer argument for the Dutch Disease real appreciation - the rise in the relative price of the non-traded good due to higher income - completely disappears. Also, demand effects alter non-traded and manufacturing output but have no impact on the agricultural sector. The world-price effect is the sole cause of the decline in the agricultural sector in the long run.
ER  - 

