AB  - This paper argues that the process of determination of daily wage-rate in rural labour markets is best seen as an act of ‘implicit co-operation’ among workers. Using the framework of repeated non-cooperative game, it is argued that this hypothesis can explain better than existing theories several known features of a typical South Asian rural labour market, e.g. the co- existence of involuntary unemployment with responsiveness to supply and demand, plasticity of wage-rate in some cases co-existing with rigidity in others, etc.
