AB  - This paper presents a simple model of international trade and growth between a mature, industrial region (the North) and a semi-industrial, primary exporting region (the South). Under capital autarky, per capita Southern industrial output is minimized if the North is at the Golden Rule point. Regardless of whether capital is internationally mobile, Northern transfers to the South will not necessarily raise Southern industrial output unless they reach a critical level. Additional transfers may crowd Northern private investment in the South out if this critical level is not attained. The effects of changes in saving behavior and technical progress are also studied.
